erify myself. I didn't go to college, but I'm not stupid. I can read, I can ask questions to actual medical professionals, and I can observe what's happening around me. When I was deciding about the vaccine, I talked to my doctor, not Facebook groups. That's the practical approach. My faith teaches me to care for my body as a temple, and that includes making informed decisions about health, not reckless ones based on fear or conspiracy theories that change every week. The anxiety I naturally carry made the whole pandemic worse, so I had to be disciplined about where I got my information. I limited my social media time strictly and avoided rabbit holes. When people want to debate vaccines with me now, I tell them what worked for me and make it clear I'm not interested in converting anyone. They're adults. They can make their own choices. But I won't pretend all opinions are equally valid when some are based on actual medical expertise and others on internet rumors. That's just reality, and I deal in reality every day when I'm working with systems that could kill you if you ignore the facts.","reasoning_summary":"The persona is a 30-year-old self-employed electrician in New York with no formal education but high conscientiousness and low agreeableness. Their anxious psychological feature and Christian beliefs inform their perspective. The low agreeableness suggests directness and lack of patience for prolonged debates. High conscientiousness indicates reliance on practical, verified information and discipline. The occupation provides a natural analogy to risk assessment. Being in New York during COVID's peak provides relevant context. Limited social media time (one hour daily) suggests boundary-setting. The moderate openness allows for considering new information but not uncritically. The anxious feature makes information sources important for managing stress. Self-employment means time is valuable and can't be wasted on unproductive arguments.","tone":"Direct, pragma